entry.title: [layout] Respect align-self/justify-self for abspos elements.
entry.content:
This fixes the bug that we weren't respecting align-self/justify-self

for abspos elements with both insets set.



Instead of just using the containing block "start" inset bias when

both insets are set - look at the value of align-self/justify-self

(see logic in GetAlignmentInsetBias).



Tests are validating the following:

- {align,justify}-self-*.html -> validates the correct position with

different writing-mode combinations and *-self keywords. (Tests the

complex logic in GetAlignmentInsetBias).

- safe-{align,justify}-self-*.html -> validates the safe/unsafe

behaviour with different writing-mode combinations, and "safe end".

(Tests the clamping logic in ComputeInsets).

- stretch-intrinsic-size-*.html -> validates the correct aspect-ratio

handling for stretching one axes, and the size being reflexed in

the opposite axis, with different writing-mode combinations. (Tests

the logic in ComputeOof*Dimensions and the replaced logic in

out_of_flow_layout_part.cc).

- table-{align,justify}-self-stretch.html -> validates correct table

stretching behaviour, and that tables still respect their implicit

min-intrinsic size constraint.



Placed behind blink flag: LayoutAlignForPositioned



Bug: 226252

entry.title: [ios] Do not add MVT favicon as subview of rounded background
entry.content:
With the MagicStack enabled, a UIView with clipped rounded corners

serves as the background of the MVT favicons, whereas by default

an image asset is used as the background. The theory is that adding

the favicon as a subview of the background view adds additional

processing load as UIKit take the entire view of background + favicon

when clipping, thus requiring the entire view to be "off-screen

rendered" in a buffer.



Moving the favicon as sibling to the clipped background view and still

centering it to the background results in the simulator not flagging the

layer as "color off-screen rendered".

entry.title: [ios][fixit] Don't update footer fullscreen when secondary toolbar is hidden
entry.content:
This CL fixes the issue that a toolbar on the bottom keeps remaining

when a user comes back from another app. See https://crbug.com/1488758

for the instructions to reproduce the issue.



The problem is `expandedToolbarHeight` in

`-updateFootersForFullscreenProgress:`. `expandedToolbarHeight` should

be 0 when the omnibox position is primary (= on the top). However,

in some cases, `expanded_bottom_toolbar_height_` and

`collapsed_bottom_toolbar_height_` in FullscreenModel are not

updated via BroadcastObserver before

`-updateFootersForFullscreenProgress:` is called and

`secondaryToolbarHeightConstraint.constant` is set to non-zero

value.



In the normal case,

1. `expanded_bottom_toolbar_height_` and

`collapsed_bottom_toolbar_height_` in FullscreenModel are updated via

BroadcastObserver, which makes `expandedToolbarHeight` returns 0.

2. `-updateOmniboxPosition:` is called and it eventually reaches

`-updateForFullscreenProgress:` to update the height of the secondary

toolbar, however, it doesn't change anything because the value of

`expandedToolbarHeight` is 0.



In the error case, the order of step 1 and 2 is reversed because of the

timing issue of BroadcastObserver (I guess). The height of the

secondary toolbar has non-zero value since `expandedToolbarHeight` is

not non-zero value.



Bug: 1488758

entry.title: media/VideoEncodeAccelerator::Config: Add drop_frame_thresh_percentage
entry.content:
This CL adds |drop_frame_thresh_percentage| to

VideoEncodeAccelerator::Config. It indicates the percentage of the

target data buffer and when the data buffer fallows below the

percentage, a frame is dropped - no encoded chunk is produced for the

frame. If a client doesn't want to drop a frame, then the value must

be set to zero. The default value for it is zero.

This CL sets the value to zero in all the clients. So this CL doesn't

change the original behavior.
